                            <comment id="108726" author="bfaccini" created="Wed, 4 Mar 2015 13:45:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Seb, as usual I will need the kernel-debuginfo&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;-common&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; 2x RPMs (for vmlinux and Kernel modules symbols) and also the lustre-modules and/or lustre-debugingo RPM(s) (for the Lustre modules with symbols).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="108722" author="sebastien.buisson" created="Wed, 4 Mar 2015 11:53:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Bruno,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The crash dump has been upload on ftp.whamcloud.com, under /uploads/&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-6326&quot; title=&quot;list_del corruption causes MDS crash&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-6326&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-6326&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;: the file is &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-6326&quot; title=&quot;list_del corruption causes MDS crash&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-6326&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-6326&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;-crashMDS.tar.gz.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sebastien.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="108718" author="sebastien.buisson" created="Wed, 4 Mar 2015 10:35:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ah, nice catch Bruno, it seems you have the ASCII character set in mind &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is a crash-dump available, I will upload it ASAP.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sebastien.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="108715" author="bfaccini" created="Wed, 4 Mar 2015 10:29:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Humm, the corrupted pointer value looks like something familiar when treated as an ascii string : &quot;wp-OST00&quot;, which may likely be part of an OST target lwp/LightWeightProxy name...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also, having a better look to the stack-trace of the panic&apos;ing thread, it looks like we may have faced some unexpected reentry (due to RTC interrupt) inside dcache code that&apos;s likely to be the cause of this crash.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;BTW, you did not mention if there is a crash-dump available or not?&lt;/p&gt;


</comment>
